text: NATIONAL POLICY ON SAFETY, HEALTH AND ENVIRONMENT AT WORK
label: title

text: PLACE
label: other

text: 1. PREAMBLE
label: h1

text: 1.1 The Constitution of India provide detailed provisions for the rights of the
label: other

text: citizens and also lays down the Directive Principles of State Policy which set
label: other

text: an aim to which the activities of the state are to be guided.
label: other

text: 1.2 These Directive Principles provide
label: other

text: (a) for securing the health and strength of employees, men and women;
label: other

text: b) that the tender age of children are not abused;
label: other

text: c) that citizens are not forced by economic necessity to enter avocations
label: other

text: unsuited to their age or strength;
label: other

text: d) just and humane conditions of work and maternity relief are provided;
label: other

text: and
label: other

text: e) that the Government shall take steps, by suitable legislation or in any
label: other

text: other way, to secure the participation of employee in the management of
label: other

text: undertakings, establishments or other organisations engaged in any industry.
label: other

text: 1.3 On the basis of these Directive Principles as well as international
label: other

text: instruments, Government is committed to regulate all economic activities for
label: other

text: management of safety and health risks at workplaces and to provide
label: other

text: measures so as to ensure safe and healthy working conditions for every
label: other

text: working man and woman in the nation. Government recognizes that safety
label: other

text: and health of workers has a positive impact on productivity and economic
label: other

text: and social development. Prevention is an integral part of economic activities
label: other

text: as high safety and health standard at work is as important as good business
label: other

text: performance for new as well as existing industries.
label: other

text: 1.4 The formulation of policy, priorities and strategies in occupational safety,
label: other

text: health and environment at work places, is undertaken by national authorities
label: other

text: in consultation with social partners for fulfilling such objectives. A critical
label: other

text: role is played by the Government and the social partners, professional safety
label: other

text: and health organizations in ensuring prevention and in also providing
label: other

text: treatment, support and rehabilitation services.
label: other

text: 1.5 Government of India firmly believes that without safe, clean environment as
label: other

text: well as healthy working conditions, social justice and economic growth
label: other

text: cannot be achieved and that safe and healthy working environment is
label: other

text: recognized as a fundamental human right. Education, training, consultation
label: other

text: and exchange of information and good practices are essential for prevention
label: other

text: and promotion of such measures.
label: other

text: 1.6 The changing job patterns and working relationships, the rise in self
label: other

text: employment, greater sub-contracting, outsourcing of work, homework and
label: other

text: the increasing number of employees working away from their establishment,
label: other

text: pose problems to management of occupational safety and health risks at
label: other

text: workplaces. New safety hazards and health risks will be appearing along
label: other

text: with the transfer and adoption of new technologies. In addition, many of the
label: other

text: well known conventional hazards will continue to be present at the
label: other

text: workplace till the risks arising from exposure to these hazards are brought
label: other

text: under adequate control. While advancements in technology have minimized
label: other

text: or eliminated some hazards at workplace, new risks can emerge in their place
label: other

text: which needs to be addressed.
label: other

text: 1.7 Particular attention needs to be paid to the hazardous operations and of
label: other

text: employees in risk prone conditions such as migrant employees and various
label: other

text: vulnerable groups of employees arising out of greater mobility in the
label: other

text: workforce with more people working for a number of employers, either
label: other

text: consecutively or simultaneously.
label: other

text: 1.8 The increasing use of chemicals, exposure to physical, chemical and
label: other

text: biological agents with hazard potential unknown to people; the
label: other

text: indiscriminate use of agro-chemicals including pesticides, agricultural
label: other

text: machineries and equipment; industries with major accident risks; effects of
label: other

text: computer controlled technologies and alarming influence of stress at work
label: other

text: in many modern jobs pose serious safety, health and environmental risks.
label: other

text: 1.9 The fundamental purpose of this National Policy on Safety, Health and
label: other

text: Environment at workplace, is not only to eliminate the incidence of work
label: other

text: related injuries, diseases, fatalities, disaster and loss of national assets and
label: other

text: ensuring achievement of a high level of occupational safety, health and
label: other

text: environment performance through proactive approaches but also to enhance
label: other

text: the well-being of the employee and society, at large. The necessary
label: other

text: changes in this area will be based on a co-ordinated national effort
label: other

text: focused on clear national goals and objectives.
label: other

text: 1.10 Every Ministry or Department may work out their detailed policy relevant to
label: other

text: their working environment as per the guidelines on the National Policy.
label: other

text: 2. GOALS:
label: h1

text: The Government firmly believes that building and maintaining national
label: other

text: preventive safety and health culture is the need of the hour. With a view to
label: other

text: develop such a culture and to improve the safety, health and environment at
label: other

text: work place, it is essential to meet the following requirements:-
label: other

text: 2.1 providing a statutory framework on Occupational Safety and Health in
label: other

text: respect of all sectors of industrial activities including the construction sector,
label: other

text: designing suitable control systems of compliance, enforcement and
label: other

text: incentives for better compliance.
label: other

text: 2.2 providing administrative and technical support services.
label: other

text: 2.3. providing a system of incentives to employers and employees to achieve
label: other

text: higher health and safety standards .
label: other

text: 2.4 providing for a system of non-financial incentives for improvement in safety
label: other

text: and health.
label: other

text: 2.5. establishing and developing the research and development capability in
label: other

text: emerging areas of risk and providing for effective control measures.
label: other

text: 2.6. Focusing on prevention strategies and monitoring performance through
label: other

text: improved data collection system on work related injuries and diseases.
label: other

text: 2.7 Developing and providing required technical manpower and knowledge in
label: other

text: the areas of safety, health and environment at workplaces in different sectors.
label: other

text: 2.8 Promoting inclusion of safety, health and environment, improvement at
label: other

text: workplaces as an important component in other relevant national policy
label: other

text: documents.
label: other

text: 2.9 Including safety and occupational health as an integral part of every
label: other

text: operation.
label: other

text: 3. OBJECTIVES:
label: h1

text: 3.1 The policy seeks to bring the national objectives into focus as a step towards
label: other

text: improvement in safety, health and environment at workplace. The objectives are to
label: other

text: achieve:-
label: other

text: a) Continuous reduction in the incidence of work related injuries,
label: other

text: fatalities, diseases, disasters and loss of national assets.
label: other

text: b) Improved coverage of work related injuries, fatalities and diseases and
label: other

text: provide for a more comprehensive data base for facilitating better
label: other

text: performance and monitoring.
label: other

text: c) Continuous enhancement of community awareness regarding safety,
label: other

text: health and environment at workplace related areas.
label: other

text: d) Continually increasing community expectation of workplace health
label: other

text: and safety standards.
label: other

text: e) Improving safety, health and environment at workplace by creation of
label: other

text: “green jobs” contributing to sustainable enterprise development.
label: other

label: other

label: other

label: other

text: safety, health and environment at workplaces in all economic activities

text: through an adequate and effective labour inspection system;

label: other

label: other

label: other

label: other

label: other

text: Model Report:
label: other

text: Trigger for OCHA Anticipatory Action on Drought in Chad
label: other

text: 1. Background
label: h1

text: This document summarizes the documentation and findings of the peer review of the model
label: other

text: used by the UN Central Emergency Response Fund to trigger the drought anticipatory action
label: other

text: framework in Chad. The model is a go-no-go trigger mechanism designed to anticipate
label: other

text: humanitarian impacts of seasonal drought in a sub-region of Chad.
label: other

text: The review has been conducted between January and May 2023.
label: other

text: 2. Main Findings and Recommendations
label: h1

text: You can find all the documentation regarding the model, its application and the review process
label: other

text: at the following links:
label: other

text: The Model Card describes the version of the model that was endorsed by humanitarian
label: other

text: action in November 2022 and was completed in January 2023.
label: other

text: The Model Evaluation Matrix was completed in February 2023 by Carlos Osorio-Ramírez,
label: other

text: Associate Professor at Universidad Nacional de Colombia.
label: other

text: The Implementation Plan was completed in February 2023. It summarizes how the
label: other

text: trigger model is used to trigger anticipatory action and the agreed activation protocol.
label: other

text: The Ethical Matrix aims to identify all stakeholders and potential issues regarding the
label: other

text: intended use of the model. The Ethical Matrix was completed in May 2023 by Anna Lena
label: other

text: Huhn, Southern Africa Regional Anticipatory Action Advisor at the United Nations World
label: other

text: Food Programme.
label: other

text: A summary of the main findings and recommendations is provided below.
label: other

text: 2.1 Technical Review
label: h2

text: Intended Use
label: h3

text: Overall, the use cases are well-described and adequately explained. The documentation of the
label: other

text: limitations of the model could be extended in its description, as is the case of the biomass
label: other

text: anomaly and its connection with scenarios like extreme dryness or late onset.
label: other

text: Model Development and Documentation
label: h3

text: It is advisable to provide further documentation on the different data sources used by the team
label: other

text: to validate the selection of indicators and estimate the performance of the model. Also, some
label: other

text: data is not available in a machine readable format and it would be good to explain how the team
label: other

text: dealt with this issue.
label: other

text: Model Evaluation
label: h3

text: It is unclear what is an acceptable level of accuracy for the model. The team should better
label: other

text: articulate how the performance benchmark was established and how the performance metrics
label: other

text: were evaluated and presented to the final stakeholders.
label: other

text: Operational Readiness
label: h3

text: It would be good to expand the analysis of the missed activations of the models and the
label: other

text: potential false alarms that the model could be providing.
label: other

text: 2.2 Ethical Review
label: h2

text: False Negatives
label: h3

text: A false negative occurs when no drought impact is predicted but drought conditions occur.
label: other

text: The team could consider additional mitigation strategies such as the use of citizen science or
label: other

text: ground observations to complement the forecast-based trigger.
label: other

text: Insufficient Data
label: h3

text: Insufficient data refers to the gaps in impact data used to verify the forecast predictions.
label: other

text: Insufficient data might limit the precise prediction of forecasted humanitarian impact and
label: other

text: expose local populations to adverse humanitarian impact induced by a drought event, requiring
label: other

text: a large-scale humanitarian response ex-post. The team should consider the feasibility of adding
label: other

text: further vulnerability layers in future iterations of the model.
label: other

text: False Positives
label: h3

text: A false positive happens when drought impact is predicted but no drought conditions occur.
label: other

text: Anticipatory action follows the ‘no regret’ principle, but a false alarm can still lead to inadequate
label: other

text: resource allocation with a high potential impact on affected communities. The anticipatory
label: other

text: action framework could indicate a precise mitigation strategy in a clearer manner.
label: other

text: Lack of Trust and Ownership
label: h3

text: Lack of trust and ownership refers to the limited involvement of local and regional authorities in
label: other

text: the model design and validation. This may lead to little ownership and trust put into the model
label: other

text: and eventually to political blockages in activations. In future framework versions a clear strategy
label: other

text: for the involvement of affected populations and an approach to accountability to affected
label: other

text: populations should be identified.
label: other

text: Lack of Transparency
label: h3

text: Lack of transparency refers to the algorithms not being made available or not being transparent.
label: other

text: The anticipatory action framework should reflect clearer strategies to engage with local leaders
label: other

text: to better understand what is happening on the ground and obtain early buy-in. Mitigation
label: other

text: strategy for a potential lack of transparency should be expanded in the model card and/or the
label: other

text: anticipatory action framework.
label: other

text: Inaction
label: h3

text: Inaction refers to the situation in which drought impact is predicted but no action is taken.
label: other

text: Inaction in case of trigger activation is unlikely, given the pre-allocated financing attached to it
label: other

text: and the UN-validated anticipatory action framework. Inaction might nevertheless be a
label: other

text: possibility, if government or local authorities block the roll-out of interventions on the ground or
label: other

text: in case of conflict upsurge. The team could consider adding a consensus-based
label: other

text: decision-making option around activation or non-activation in the event of specific events or
label: other

text: situational context not considered in the model design (e.g., higher levels of vulnerability or
label: other

text: increase in armed conflict, etc.)
label: other

text: Feedback
label: h3

text: The Centre invites individuals and organizations working in the humanitarian, academic,
label: other

text: research and private sector to engage with us on the peer review process. Please send feedback
label: other

text: on the Framework to centrehumdata@un.org .
label: other

text: U.S. Department of Health and Human Services
label: other

text: Dr. Lurie is the Assistant Secretary for Preparedness and Response (ASPR) at the U.S.
label: other

text: Department of Health and Human Services (HHS). As such, she serves as the Secretary's
label: other

text: principal advisor on matters related to bioterrorism and other public health emergencies.
label: other

text: Her office is the lead agency for federal public health and medical preparedness and
label: other

text: response, helping the nation prepare for, respond to, and recover from disasters.
label: other

text: Prior to her current position, she served as Senior Natural Scientist and Paul O’ Neill
label: other

text: Alcoa Professor of Health Policy at the RAND Corporation. There she directed RAND’s
label: other

text: public health and preparedness work as well as RAND’s Center for Population Health
label: other

text: and Health Disparities. She has previously served in federal government, as Principal
label: other

text: Deputy Assistant Secretary of Health in the HHS; in state government as Medical
label: other

text: Advisor to the Commissioner at the Minnesota Department of Health; and in academia,
label: other

text: as Professor in the University of Minnesota Schools of Medicine and Public Health. Dr.
label: other

text: Lurie has a long history in the health services research field, primarily in the areas of
label: other

text: access to and quality of care, managed care, mental health, prevention, public health
label: other

text: infrastructure and preparedness and health disparities.
label: other

text: Dr. Lurie attended college and medical school at the University of Pennsylvania, and
label: other

text: completed her residency and MSPH at UCLA, where she was also a Robert Wood
label: other

text: Johnson Foundation Clinical Scholar. She served as Senior Editor for Health Services
label: other

text: Research and has served on editorial boards and as a reviewer for numerous journals.
label: other

text: She has served on the council and was President of the Society of General Internal
label: other

text: Medicine, and on the board of directors for Academy Health, and has served on multiple
label: other

text: other national committees. She is the recipient of numerous awards, including the AHSR
label: other

text: Young Investigator Award, the Nellie Westerman Prize for Research in Ethics, the
label: other

text: Heroine in Health Care Award, the University of Pennsylvania School of Medicine’s
label: other

text: Distinguished Alumni Award, and is a member of the Institute of Medicine.
label: other

text: Dr. Lurie continues to practice clinical medicine in the health care safety net in
label: other

text: Congressman Travis Childers Backs Investigation of Economic Crisis, Votes for Final Passage of Fraud
label: title

text: Congressman Travis Childers Backs Investigation of Economic Crisis, Votes for Final
label: other

text: Passage of Fraud Enforcement and Recovery Act
label: other

text: Washington, DC - Congressman Travis Childers (D-MS) today joined a majority of his
label: other

text: colleagues in supporting final passage of the Fraud Enforcement and Recovery Act of 2009,
label: other

text: which won bipartisan House approval by a vote of 367 to 59. The legislation will provide critical
label: other

text: funding and tools to help law enforcement pursue and prosecute the type of fraud many blame
label: other

text: for the worst financial crisis in decades, and establishes a bipartisan commission to investigate
label: other

text: the causes of the financial system's collapse and the ensuing recession.
label: other

text: The bill passed in the Senate on April 28 by a vote of 92 to 4.
label: other

text: "In the face of today's economic crisis, hard working North Mississippians have lost their
label: other

text: homes, their savings, and their jobs. This bill demands oversight and accountability from the
label: other

text: fraudulent institutions that got us into this mess," said Congressman Childers.
label: other

text: "When I voted twice against TARP authorization, I disapproved that it lacked adequate
label: other

text: oversight and accountability when it came to spending billions of hard-earned taxpayer dollars.
label: other

text: Today, I am proud to support the Fraud Enforcement and Recovery Act to help determine the
label: other

text: causes of our current financial troubles, hold the responsible institutions accountable, and
label: other

text: ensure that these problems do not happen again. This important legislation also calls for the
label: other

text: diligent tracking of the funds it authorizes for these investigations, adding another level of
label: other

text: transparency to the process."
label: other

text: The Fraud Enforcement and Recovery Act is the latest in a series of consumer protection
label: other

text: reforms recently passed by the House. Last week, the House passed the Credit Cardholders'
label: other

text: Bill of Rights, which includes tough new protections for consumers facing excessive credit card
label: other

text: fees, sky-high interest rates and unfair agreements that credit card companies revise at will.
label: other

text: Later this week, the House is expected to vote on the Mortgage Reform and Anti-Predatory
label: other

text: Lending Act to curb abusive and predatory lending.
label: other

text: Congressman Travis Childers Backs Investigation of Economic Crisis, Votes for Final Passage of Fraud
label: other

text: The following measures are included in the Fraud Enforcement and Recovery Act of 2009:
label: h1

text: - Prohibits fraudulent activities involving the Troubled Assets Relief Program (TARP) or a
label: other

text: federal economic stimulus, recovery, or rescue plan.
label: other

text: - Authorizes appropriations to the Attorney General for FY 2010-FY2011 for investigations,
label: other

text: prosecutions, and civil proceedings involving federal assistance programs and financial
label: other

text: institutions. Allocates such funds among various departments of the Department of Justice
label: other

text: (DOJ).
label: other

text: - Requires the Attorney General, in consultation with the U.S. Postal Inspection Service, the
label: other

text: Inspector General for HUD, and the Secretary of Homeland Security, to submit a joint report to
label: other

text: Congress identifying: 1) amounts spent for investigations, with a certification of compliance that
label: other

text: funds have been spent in accordance with this Act, and 2) amounts recovered from criminal or
label: other

text: civil restitution, fines, penalties, and other monetary recoveries.
label: other

text: - Authorizes appropriations to the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) for
label: other

text: FY2010-FY2011 for investigations and enforcement proceedings involving financial institutions
label: other

text: and for the SEC Office of the Inspector General.
label: other

text: - Establishes the bipartisan congressional Financial Markets Commission to examine the
label: other

text: causes of the current U.S. financial and economic crisis, taking into account fraud and abuse in
label: other

text: the financial sector and other specified factors. Requires the Commission to submit a report on
label: other

text: its finding to the President and Congress on December 15, 2010. Requires the Commission
label: other

text: chairperson to appear before specified congressional committees within 120 days after the
label: other

text: submission of the report.
label: other

text: - Establishes a congressional Select Committee on Investigation of the Economic Crisis to
label: other

text: study and investigate the facts and circumstances giving rise to the current U.S. economic crisis
label: other

text: and to recommend actions to prevent a recurrence of such crisis. Requires the Select
label: other

text: Committee to submit initial, updated, and final reports on its investigation to Congress with
label: other

text: findings and recommendations.

text: 3G - WATER RIGHTS ADJUDICATION
label: title

text: Adjudication of water rights through the state courts should be completed to fully define
label: other

text: and quantify all state, tribal and federal water rights.
label: other

text: Discussion:
label: h1

text: The purpose of a general stream adjudication is to provide certainty and predictability in the
label: other

text: administration and distribution of water diverting from hydraulically connected water sources. The
label: other

text: need for a general adjudication of water rights in the Snake River Basin became apparent as the
label: other

text: spring flows in the Thousand Springs reach began to decline and disputes arose over the availability
label: other

text: of water supplies on the Snake River Plain. As part of the 1984 Swan Falls Agreement, the State
label: other

text: agreed to commence the Snake River Basin Adjudication, the largest legal proceeding in the history
label: other

text: of the state. The SRBA is the cornerstone for the long-term management of the Snake River Basin
label: other

text: within Idaho. At the conclusion of the SRBA, the state will have a listing of all water rights within the
label: other

text: basin, which is the predicate for establishing water districts to administer all water rights in
label: other

text: accordance with the prior appropriation doctrine, as established by law.
label: other

text: Pursuant to Idaho Code § 42-1734(3), the IWRB is authorized to represent the state, when requested
label: other

text: to do so by the Governor, in proceedings, negotiations, and hearings involving the federal
label: other

text: government. In the SRBA, the IWRB coordinated state participation in the negotiation of federal
label: other

text: reserved water rights, including tribal claims. The IWRB successfully negotiated agreements
label: other

text: resolving federal reserved right claims including those filed by the Shoshone-Bannock, Nez Perce,
label: other

text: and Shoshone-Paiute tribes as well as the claims of numerous federal agencies. The final settlement
label: other

text: of the Nez Perce Tribe’s claims reflected the tribe’s and the state’s shared interest in addressing
label: other

text: environmental concerns and addressed the conflicting demands for consumptive and nonconsumptive
label: other

text: uses. Consistent with state law, Tt he IWRB should serve as the lead agency for coordinating state
label: other

text: participation in all general stream adjudications.
label: other

text: On November 12, 2008, the district court ordered the commencement of an adjudication in the Coeur
label: other

text: d’Alene Spokane River water system. Like the SRBA, the determination of all existing water rights
label: other

text: from the water basins in Northern Idaho will provide the basis for administration of water rights in
label: other

text: accordance with the prior appropriation doctrine, as established by law.
label: other

text: National Teacher Appreciation Week 2012
label: title

text: Written by Mike Honda
label: other

text: Wednesday, 09 May 2012 12:13
label: other

text: Today, as part of National Teacher Appreciation Week, I want to thank each and every teacher
label: other

text: for their amazing service to their students and this country.
label: other

text: On April 24 President Obama honored California Teacher, Rebecca Mieliwock, as Teacher of
label: other

text: th
label: other

text: the Year in an event held at the White House. During the event on the 24 the
label: other

text: th,
label: other

text: President sagely articulated that teachers in this country are not just working for their students
label: other

text: or for their schools, but for the forward progress of our entire country. The American dream is
label: other

text: first ignited in the classroom; only through effective support and funding of educators’ crucial
label: other

text: work can we hope to keep America exceptional in the 21
label: other

text: st
label: other

text: Century.
label: other

text: In February, Secretary of Education Arne Duncan announced the RESPECT Program, an effort
label: other

text: to promote collaborative teaching and professional development. It is an appropriate acronym
label: other

text: and attribute for this profession. As an educator of more than 30 years, I have boundless
label: other

text: respect for those that embrace the awesome responsiblity of educating our children. Teachers
label: other

text: must have our boundless gratitude, support and respect every day of the year.
label: other

text: Many people can point back to one teacher or class experience in elementary, high school or
label: other

text: college that made a big impact on their life. This is the immense affect teachers have upon
label: other

text: students. I can still remember Mr. Williams, my chemistry and physics teacher, at San Jose
label: other

text: High School. It was through his influence and impact that I pursued a degree in the sciences at
label: other

text: San Jose State University. A path that led me to become a teacher myself, a principal, a
label: other

text: school board leader and ultimately a champion for teachers and students in Congress.
label: other

text: I encourage everyone during National Teacher Appreciation Week, to take a moment to
label: other

text: remember their favorite teacher and to share a story with your family, friends and colleagues.
label: other

text: America’s continued and future success begins with each teacher and student. Educators from
